items.title: Caladenia pusilla
items.content_text: Tiny plant. As tall as the length of my little finger. New species record for the Pyrete Range.

items.title: Muscari armeniacum
items.content_text: Two patches of a dozen or so plants at this location.

items.title: Acacia aculeatissima
items.content_text: The population in this area appears to consist wholly of plants with hairy phyllodes. This is a rarely seen occurrence for A. aculeatissima (see VicFlora entry). I've checked other NatureShare records and hairy phyllodes occur only in the northern Pyrete but not in surrounding areas (eg. Brisbane Range, Riddells Creek, Whittlesea, Kilmore, Blackwood - all of which have glabrous phyllodes).

items.title: Pauridia vaginata var. vaginata
items.content_text: Good view of the single, large, sheathing bracteole on the flower stem. Leaves with margins with irregularly spaced, small tooth-like outgrowths.

items.title: Moraea fugacissima
items.content_text: No plants seen until afternoon sun appeared, then there were hundreds.

items.title: Myriophyllum striatum
items.content_text: A few plants in the last remaining rocky pools, sharing the pools with tadpoles.

items.title: Hyalosperma glutinosum subsp. glutinosum
items.content_text: Plants are about twice the size of the more widespread H. semisterile.

items.title: Pterostylis concinna
items.content_text: Photo shows the brown, notched labellum which distinguishes Pterostylis concinna from P. nana.

items.title: Rhodanthe stricta
items.content_text: New location for this plant at Neds. This species is only known at Neds and one other location in Victoria.

items.title: Rhodanthe stricta
items.content_text: New location for this plant at Neds. This species is only known at Neds and one other location in Victoria.

items.title: Hypoxis vaginata var. vaginata
items.content_text: New species record for this collection. Found in the area burnt in last year's January wildfire. Large sheathing bracteole visible in second pic. As a result of this observation and analysis of herbarium samples, the VicFlora entry was updated to include "Leaves (with) margins, at least toward base, usually with irregularly spaced, small tooth-like outgrowths."

items.title: Pterostylis concinna
items.content_text: New species record for Barrm Birrm, Riddells Creek and the Macedon Range. One clump of about 1m diameter.

items.title: Hypoxis glabella var. glabella
items.content_text: New species record for this collection. Found in the area burnt in last year's January wildfire. This record is possibly an example of cleistogamy or apomixis in this species, with many plants flowering at this time too.

items.title: Hypoxis glabella var. glabella
items.content_text: New species record for this collection. Found in the area burnt in last year's January wildfire. Last photo shows 2 bracteoles on a very short flowering stem.

items.title: Crassula sieberiana s.s.
items.content_text: New species record for this collection. Found in the area burnt in last year's January wildfire.

items.title: Acacia pycnantha
items.content_text: New species record for this collection. Just one plant appeared on eastern edge of biosite area.

items.title: Drosera aberrans
items.content_text: New species record for this collection. Found in the area burnt in last year's January wildfire.

items.title: Brachyscome melanocarpa
items.content_text: 10 or so plants on the edge of a very lush depression. This is the second known population of this  plant in Victoria. Peter Barnes led us to this population which he has known about for many years. ID confirmed by Neville Walsh.

items.title: Hypoxis glabella var. glabella
items.content_text: New species record for Neds Corner. ID confirmed by Neville Walsh. Photos show some features required for determination at species level (eg. two non-sheathing bracteoles towards the base of the flower stem - see 3rd photo). This taxon has recently changed name from Hypoxis glabella.

items.title: Brachyscome melanocarpa
items.content_text: Location is where the species was discovered in Victoria in 2011.

items.title: Brachyscome melanocarpa
items.content_text: Location is where this species was discovered for Victoria in 2011, until now the only population known in Victoria. The plant in the first two pics was in dry soil at the outer edge of a gilgai and exposed to full sun. This made this plant a little depauperate. This plant also had the best flower at this location. Plants were found both sides of the track in the numerous small depressions/gilgais, always at the outer edge of the depression.

items.title: Amphibromus spp.
items.content_text: ID to genus by Neville Walsh. A few plants growing in and beside our patch of creek (Sandy Creek). Pic shows the distinctive membranous ligule of the Amphibromus genus.

items.title: Eucalyptus rubida
items.content_text: There are perhaps 100 trees like this in this large, open paddock, making it a very significant block of land. Unfortunately the block is a horse riding complex so plant variety in the understorey is limited.

items.title: Eucalyptus leucoxylon subsp. pruinosa
items.content_text: Shows what appears to be wax on fruit and branchlet.

items.title: Eucalyptus leucoxylon subsp. pruinosa
items.content_text: Pic shows single bud - it was the only bud I could find. Flowers were in 2s without exception at this location.

items.title: Eucalyptus leucoxylon subsp. pruinosa
items.content_text: Shows signature pruinose (waxy) covering on juvenile leaves and associated branchlets. 3rd pic shows branchlet covered in wax and pic 4 shows the same branchlet with wax rubbed off.

items.title: Eucalyptus leucoxylon subsp. pruinosa
items.content_text: First pic shows pruinose (waxy) covering on bud part of flower. Note flowers were always held in 2s at this location.

items.title: Cassytha melantha
items.content_text: Black sepals are a key feature of this species (hence the name melantha). Pic 3 has a small insect on it, possibly a Hemiptera.

items.title: Acacia suaveolens, Epacris impressa var. impressa
Acacia suaveolens
items.content_text: Notable purplish seedpods.

items.title: Acacia myrtifolia
items.content_text: Unusual for its distinctive buds.

items.title: Epacris impressa var. impressa
items.content_text: Mass displays of white Epacris impressa growing with pink Epacris in this SW corner of Anglesea Heath - see pic 4. In other places there are pink Epacris and white L. virgatus growing en masse but here L. virgatus seems to have been replaced by white Epacris.

items.title: Mycena subgalericulata
items.content_text: Growing in a fallen log.

items.title: Acacia suaveolens
items.content_text: Occasional mass flowering on roadsides, especially in gullies. Here plants were 2m+ along roadside, occasionally broken up with pink Epacris impressa.

items.title: Leucopogon virgatus var. virgatus
items.content_text: Mass displays of L. virgatus growing with pink (no white) Epacris impressa in this SW corner of Anglesea Heath. In other places there are pink and white Epacris growing en masse but here L. virgatus seems to have displaced white Epacris.

items.title: Epacris impressa var. impressa
items.content_text: Magnificent displays of Epacris in this SW corner of Anglesea Heath. At this location the Epacris were all red and mass flowering with Leucopogon virgatus, Acacia suaveolens and with Banksia marginata sprinked through.

items.title: Leucopogon woodsii

items.title: Correa reflexa var. angustifolia
items.content_text: Could be var. angustifolia? Leaves have an unusually high length:width ratio.

items.title: Boronia coerulescens subsp. coerulescens
items.content_text: Surprised me to see a few plants flowering this time of year (June). Third pic shows blue(-ish) bud that gives rise to the plant's common name.

items.content_text: At the end of the short track to Grevillea Lookout.

items.title: Wahlenbergia luteola
items.content_text: Lots of plants flowering inside and outside of a burnt area. Flowers lacked yellow colouring on the underside of petals, usually a key feature of W. luteola, but the leaves are all opposite, a feature that separates luteola from communis.

items.title: Solenogyne dominii

items.title: Anhinga novaehollandiae

items.title: Correa backhouseana var. backhouseana

items.title: Santalum lanceolatum
items.content_text: Pendulous branchlets is a key feature of this species.

items.title: Argiope protensa
items.content_text: Spotted among native veg where it had one of those thin lines/web between two low shrubs. The shrubs were about 1m apart.

items.title: Festuca muelleri
items.content_text: Tall, wide, thick, robust grass. One plant on the dirt roadside heading down from the Horn.

items.title: Acacia gunnii
items.content_text: Pretty sure this is the first record of this species on the Vic. Volcanic Plains. Growing in typical habitat for this species; ie. dry, rocky site, lacking taller shrubs, relatively large distances between grass tussocks.

items.title: Grevillea rosmarinifolia
items.content_text: Foliage is quite flexible, with a slight sharpness to the tip. Growing on a cliff face / escarpment with fully grown Bursaria, Callitris and other fully grown plants. I mention fully grown because the attached (3 plants seen) was 50cm tall by 1m wide (possibly a bit less). Plants were very woody so probably old. There are no plants above the escarpment, which was Grey Box with wildflower understorey. There are no grevilleas recorded anywhere near here. It is a form of rosmarinifolia.

items.title: Plantago muelleri
items.content_text: Scapes short at flowering stage so that flowers are among leaf bases - scapes elongating after flowering so fruit held well above the leaves.

items.title: Senecio glomeratus subsp. glomeratus
items.content_text: 3 plants together then no more seen elsewhere at this site. Not recorded previously here so I wouldn't be surprised if it were an occasional blow-in.

items.title: Craspedia adenophora
items.content_text: Discolorous leaves.

items.title: Senecio pinnatifolius var. alpinus
items.content_text: This occurs all over the treeless herbfields and is mostly smaller than that pictured here - often a single stem.

items.title: Epilobium spp.
items.content_text: All plants seen were growing in an alpine stream. Flowers seemed to be of the more common, small size rather than the larger gunnianum size.

items.content_text: Flighless grasshopper. Female (left) is about twice as large as male (right).

items.title: Acripeza reticulata

items.title: Euphrasia crassiuscula subsp. glandulifera
items.content_text: Most plants of this subspecies had finished flowering st this time. This was the only plant found with reasonable flowers remaining. This grows alongside subsp. eglandulosa which was in the peak of its flowering time.

items.title: Prasophyllum alpestre
items.content_text: Very common across the whole of the Bogong High Plains.

items.title: Podolepis robusta
items.content_text: Occurs here with sp. aff. robusta (NW Alps) which has hairy leaves (looks greyish, especially on upper stem), more yellow flowers and, at this location, longer ligules.

items.title: Podolepis sp. aff. robusta (N.E. Alps)
items.content_text: At this location it occurs with P. robusta which has glabrous leaves, more orangey flowers and shorter ligules.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: Pretty Valley Ponds and surrounding swamp is a flora haven.

items.title: Gentianella cunninghamii subsp. cunninghamii
items.content_text: Very common across the Bogong High Plains.

items.title: Myriophyllum pedunculatum
items.content_text: Probably subsp. pedunculatum. Growing in black clay, moist depressions, in the swamps/bogs of Pretty Valley.

items.title: Carex gaudichaudiana
items.content_text: Growing in black clay, moist depressions, in the swamps/bogs of Pretty Valley.

items.title: Carpha nivicola
items.content_text: Wide leaves suggests nivicola.

items.title: Epacris glacialis
items.content_text: These were the only flowers seen.

items.title: Lobelia surrepens
items.content_text: Small and larger moist depressions (pic 2) in the Pretty Valley swamps were often dominated by L. surrepens.

items.title: Stylidium montanum
items.content_text: One small patch of plants at the low point of a saddle (probably where water gathers) on track to Mt Nelse. S. armeria armeria occasionally on either side. Short leaves and rhizomatous clumping (2nd pic) are key features for S. montanum.

items.title: Craspedia alba
items.content_text: Just this single population known in Victoria. Grows in only a dozen or so moist depressions in this alpine herbfield on black peaty mud. The depressions (see final pic) that contain C. alba are generally about 2-3m x 4m. All plants had finished flowering and gone to seed except for this one and a couple more that had past their best.

items.title: Acrothamnus montanus
items.content_text: All shrubs in this windswept alpine heathland reach a height of about 50cm. Could be A. hookeri but predominantly flat leaves indicates A. montanus.

items.title: Amyema quandang var. quandang
items.content_text: Growing on Acacia dealbata subsp. dealbata.

items.title: Leycesteria formosa
items.content_text: Growing creekside on Steavenson River.

items.title: Lonicera tatarica
items.content_text: Came up in in-laws' garden. It was 1.5m tall when we pulled it out. Could be first record in Australia.

items.title: Opiliones spp.
items.content_text: At the main cafe, Lake Mountain. Spotted by Ellena Best. Pretty sure this is a Harvestman. It would be the first recorded on NatureShare.

items.title: Senecio linearifolius var. denticulatus
items.content_text: Lots of young plants coming up close to the Baw Baw Alpine Village. S. linearifolius var. latifolius also grows nearby and it is probably one month ahead of var. denticulatus re flowering time.

items.title: Eusynthemis spp.
items.content_text: Can't see labrum so can't ID to species. It is E. guttata or tillyardi.

items.title: Gonocarpus micranthus subsp. micranthus
items.content_text: Growing beside an alpine bog. Tiny plant and tiny flowers.

items.title: Thysanotus tuberosus subsp. tuberosus
items.content_text: Despite 2/3 leaves and low-branching flower stem (which could lead to T. juncifolius on the plantnet key) this tuberosus.

items.title: Senecio velleioides
items.content_text: Small patch growing alongside the far more widespread S. linearifolius var. latifolius.

items.title: Hovea montana
items.content_text: Sprawling as a groundcover.

items.title: Platyzosteria spp.

items.title: Tasmannia xerophila subsp. xerophila
items.content_text: 2-3 flowers/fruit per pedicel (developing fruit here - see pic 2 for close-up). Leaf apex obtuse (not acute) is another feature of xerophila distinguishing it from lanceolata. T. xerophila is common around the peak of Lake Mountain.

items.title: Graphium macleayanus moggana, Stylidium armeria subsp. armeria
items.content_text: Butterfly was flying from flower to flower on the one plant, hovering with wings flapping rapidly while feeding, then moving on to the next plant. Flowers didn't appear to trigger. A few butterflies were seen doing this. Host plant here will be Tasmannia xerophila which is plentiful.

items.title: Baeckea gunniana

items.title: Dryopoa dives subsp. dives
items.content_text: Pic 3 gives an idea of the height of plants, at 2.5-3m.

items.content_text: Lots on a Cherry Ballart (Exocarpos cupressiformis). I notice there are a few pics on the internet of this species on Exocarpos species. They are adept at hiding, by moving to the other side of the twig/branch they are on.

items.content_text: One butterfly exhibiting aggressive, territorial behaviour towards other butterflies. Flying between three large flowering Senecio linearifolius linearifolius plants, shooing off all who came near. It never landed and I couldn't get a photo with my phone.

items.title: Senecio linearifolius var. linearifolius

items.content_text: About half the size of the other common, large red Netelia wasp seen at this location. ID as Netelia spp. by Ken Walker who is also not sure it is Netelia spp.. Ken added "There are several genera (eg: Enicophilus, Ophion, Leptophion, Riekophion etc) that all have the same body shape and colour. The wing venation is the key to distinguishing these genera. I have punted for Netelia as and identification because I believe I can see a small triangular cell on the outer margins of the forewings."

items.title: Elachanthus pusillus
items.content_text: Red-tipped and fringed bracts are a key feature of this species. Single individual of this tiny herb found among large numbers of Elachanthus glaber covering an area of just about 20m x 10m. Elachanthus pusillus is considerably smaller than E. glaber and has red-tipped and fringed apex to bracts plus bristly-hairy leaves. E. glaber has none of these features.
